-- Article 37: Benign Breast Diseases
-- Surgery 2 CME Content

-- Insert sections

FIBROADENOMA: Most common breast lump in women under 30. Well-circumscribed, mobile (breast mouse), firm, non-tender. Arises from complete lobule (stromal and epithelial). Giant fibroadenoma is greater than 5cm. Phyllodes tumor is rare, may be malignant, requires wide excision. Management: observation if typical; excision if greater than 3cm, growing, or patient preference.

BREAST CYSTS: Common in 35-50 age group. May be solitary or multiple. Present as smooth, tense lumps that may be tender. Diagnosed and treated by aspiration - clear or green fluid, disappearance of lump, no bloody aspirate. No further action if these criteria met. Recurrent cysts may need excision.

FIBROCYSTIC CHANGE: Most common cause of breast lumps. Includes fibrosis, cysts, adenosis, epithelial hyperplasia. Presents with cyclical mastalgia, nodularity, and lumpiness. Management is reassurance, supportive bra, evening primrose oil, danazol for severe cases.'),
('d0000037-0000-0000-0000-000000000037'::uuid, 'content', 3, 'Breast Infections and Nipple Conditions', 'LACTATIONAL MASTITIS: Staphylococcus aureus most common. Presents with painful, red, swollen breast with fever. Treat with flucloxacillin and continue breastfeeding. Abscess requires drainage - ultrasound-guided aspiration or surgical incision.

NON-LACTATIONAL MASTITIS: Periductal mastitis (smokers), granulomatous mastitis, tuberculosis. Periductal mastitis associated with nipple piercing and smoking - often anaerobic bacteria. May lead to mammary duct fistula.

BREAST ABSCESS: Lactational - peripheral location; non-lactational - periareolar location. US-guided aspiration first-line; surgical drainage if fails or large abscess. Always exclude inflammatory carcinoma in non-lactational abscess.

NIPPLE DISCHARGE: Physiological (bilateral, multiple ducts), pathological (unilateral, single duct, spontaneous). Milky - galactorrhea (prolactinoma). Green or brown - duct ectasia. Bloody - papilloma, carcinoma (requires investigation). Serous - fibrocystic change.

FAT NECROSIS: History of trauma or surgery. Firm, irregular mass mimicking carcinoma. Oil cyst on mammogram. Core biopsy confirms diagnosis. No treatment needed.'),
('d0000037-0000-0000-0000-000000000037'::uuid, 'content', 4, 'Investigation and Triple Assessment', 'TRIPLE ASSESSMENT: Clinical examination, imaging (mammogram plus ultrasound), and tissue diagnosis (cytology or histology). All three components must be concordant.

IMAGING: Under 35 years - ultrasound first (dense breast tissue). Over 35 years - mammogram plus or minus ultrasound. MRI for implant assessment, BRCA screening, occult primary.

TISSUE DIAGNOSIS: Fine needle aspiration cytology (FNAC) - C1-C5 grading. Core biopsy - provides histology, preferred for solid lesions. B1-B5 grading. Vacuum-assisted biopsy for microcalcifications.

GRADING SYSTEMS: C1 or B1 - inadequate; C2 or B2 - benign; C3 or B3 - atypical, probably benign; C4 or B4 - suspicious; C5 or B5 - malignant.

HIGH-RISK LESIONS: Atypical ductal hyperplasia (ADH), atypical lobular hyperplasia (ALH), lobular carcinoma in situ (LCIS), radial scar, papillary lesions. Require excision biopsy and surveillance.'),
('d0000037-0000-0000-0000-000000000037'::uuid, 'clinical_pearls', 5, 'Clinical Pearls', 'Fibroadenoma is mobile breast mouse - common under 30. Cyst aspiration: clear fluid plus lump disappears plus no mass equals no further action. Bloody nipple discharge requires investigation - papilloma or carcinoma. Lactational mastitis - continue breastfeeding. Non-lactational abscess - always exclude inflammatory carcinoma. Fat necrosis mimics carcinoma - history of trauma. Triple assessment is mandatory for any breast lump.'),
('d0000037-0000-0000-0000-000000000037'::uuid, 'key_points', 6, 'Key Points Summary', 'ANDI framework explains benign breast disease as aberrations of normal development and involution. Fibroadenoma: mobile, firm, well-circumscribed lump in young women. Cyst: aspirate, reassure if criteria met. Fibrocystic change is most common cause of breast lumps. Lactational mastitis: Staph aureus, flucloxacillin, continue breastfeeding. Periductal mastitis associated with smoking. Bloody discharge: papilloma most common cause. Triple assessment for all breast lumps.');

